‘You prate of ancient genealogies and wars, but never a word do you say on the real questions of the moment-how much we shall pay fora jar of wine, how, where, aud when we shall drink. Come, a toast to the Moon‚ to the Night, to our friend Murena, the augur. The wine shall be mixed as your tastes deumnd3 give music, scatter flowers, and let old Lycus hear our din and envy our light loves.²

Horace thus dramatically portraysa company which has fallen into serious conversation on mythological subjects, and forgotten the pur· pose of the gathering. ln the first two strophes he recalls bis compan- ions from their soberer talk3 then suddenly assuming the character of magister bi'bendi, he names the toastS, the strength of the wine that shall be used, and calls for flowers and music. The occasion for the ode may have been a symposium in Murena's honor (v. 10 f.)‚ but it is more likely that the poet's imagination gave the impulse for the lines. They should be compared with C. 1, 27. The date of composition cannot be determined. Metre, 71.
